4.5	We reiterated our recommendation that management:
Maintain a ledger card for each class of Property, Plant and Equipment to support the balances presented in the FS and ensure that the basis of computation of the depreciation expenses is correct;
Prioritize the reconciliation of balances between the accounting records and RPCPPE. Prepare  adjusting  entries,  if any, to reflect the correct balances of the affected accounts in the FS.

We recommended that management:
immediately submit justifiable reasons on the deficiencies noted in order to avoid the disallowance thereof;
require the concerned contractor to immediately install the necessary item of work on the construction of livelihood center and homestay otherwise, the amount of P 36,835.16 shall be deducted from his claim and appropriate sanctions shall be imposed pursuant to the provisions of RA 9184;
require the concerned contractor to immediately settle the liquidated damages or it shall be deducted from his claim and appropriate sanctions shall be imposed pursuant to the provisions of RA 9184;
The materials not presented should be delivered to the agency to avoid disallowance thereof.

4 We reiterated our recommendation that management adopt the following measures in order to prevent further accumulation of outstanding cash advances:
Compel the accountable officers concerned to immediately liquidate their cash advances and demand refund of their unused balances, otherwise, appropriate charges be filed against them for malversation of public funds and failure to render accounts;
Elected officials should not be granted cash advances other than for traveling expenses only consistent with Section 4.1.4 of COA Circular No. 97-002;
Exert extra efforts towards collections through cash settlements of long overdue unliquidated cash advances of officials and employees who are no longer connected with the Municipal Government;
Request for write-off of long outstanding cash advances whose creditors are no longer located/deceased, if warranted; and
Comply strictly with the provisions of COA Circular No.97-002, COA Accounting Circular No. 2006-001 and other laws, rules and regulations relative to the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances. Stop granting new cash advances to officials and employees with outstanding/unliquidated cash advance.

Require the Accounting Office to religiously post all liquidation reports of cash advances submitted to them.

In order to foster public awareness and monitoring of the procurement process and implementation of perfected and awarded contracts, we recommended that:

) The Bids and Awards Committee ensure the posting of the Notice of Award, Notice to Proceed and approved contracts in the PHILGEPS and in the website of the LGU for all their procurement activities.
) The BAC prepares Procurement Monitoring Report (PMR) for all types of procurement at the end of each semester and has the report approved by the HOPE.

25.6 We recommended that management:
immediately submit justifiable reasons on the deficiencies noted in order to avoid the disallowance thereof;
require the concerned contractor to immediately install the necessary item of work on the construction of livelihood center and homestay otherwise, the amount of P 36,835.16 shall be deducted from his claim and appropriate sanctions shall be imposed pursuant to the provisions of RA 9184;
require the concerned contractor to immediately settle the liquidated damages or it shall be deducted from his claim and appropriate sanctions shall be imposed pursuant to the provisions of RA 9184;
The materials not presented should be delivered to the agency to avoid disallowance thereof.

We reiterated our recommendation that management adopt the following measures in order to prevent further accumulation of outstanding cash advances:

a. Compel the accountable officers concerned to immediately liquidate their cash advances and demand refund of their unused balances, otherwise, appropriate charges be filed against them for malversation of public funds and failure to render accounts;
b. Elected officials should not be granted cash advances other than for traveling expenses only consistent with Section 4.1.4 of COA Circular No. 97-002;

c. Exert extra efforts towards collections through cash settlements of long overdue unliquidated cash advances of officials and employees who are no longer connected with the Municipal Government;

d. Request for write-off of long outstanding cash advances whose creditors are no longer located/deceased, if warranted; and

e. Comply strictly with the provisions of COA Circular No.97-002, COA Accounting Circular No. 2006-001 and other laws, rules and regulations relative to the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances. Stop granting new cash advances to officials and employees with outstanding or unliquidated cash advances.

16.7 In order to foster public awareness and monitoring of the procurement process
and implementation of perfected and awarded contracts, we recommended that:
) The Bids and Awards Committee ensure the posting of the Notice of Award, Notice to Proceed and approved contracts in the PHILGEPS and in the website of the LGU for all their procurement activities.
) The BAC prepare Procurement Monitoring Report (PMR) for all types of procurement at the end of each semester and have the report approved by the HOPE.

We recommended that the management:

A. Stop the practice of using trust funds for payment of regular expenditures to avoid further incurrence of cash overdraft. Likewise, prompt remittance of trust funds due to other government agencies must be undertaken to avoid misappropriation thereof.;

B. Limit the incurrence of obligations to the extent of cash availability;

C. Set aside in the 2016 annual budget mandatory reserve in order that the amounts utilized for other purposes out of trust funds shall be returned; and

D. Regulate the hiring of job orders/ casuals /contractual and the granting of financial assistance and austerity measures must be adopted by the LGU.
